00:48:00.620 --> 00:48:07.590
So it's something you
can study first, and then

00:48:07.590 --> 00:48:10.920
make your life a little easier.

00:48:10.920 --> 00:48:17.710
So what we're going to do now
for the rest of the lecture

00:48:17.710 --> 00:48:20.330
is consider the
variational problem, which

00:48:20.330 --> 00:48:24.100
is something you probably
haven't seen before,

00:48:24.100 --> 00:48:25.475
the variational problem.

00:48:38.450 --> 00:48:43.410
This problem has to do with
calculus of variations.

00:48:43.410 --> 00:48:45.680
Now, calculus of
variations is something

00:48:45.680 --> 00:48:49.200
considered fairly advanced.

00:48:49.200 --> 00:48:52.535
And therefore, as
you will see, we

00:48:52.535 --> 00:48:57.390
will avoid some of the major
difficulties of calculus

00:48:57.390 --> 00:49:01.930
of variations in our discussion
of the variational principle.

00:49:01.930 --> 00:49:11.860
But I wanted to mention a
little story about this problem.

00:49:11.860 --> 00:49:18.590
So this calculus of variations
is a more complicated version

00:49:18.590 --> 00:49:26.140
of maxima and minima in which in
maxima and minima of functions

00:49:26.140 --> 00:49:27.800
you look at the function.

00:49:27.800 --> 00:49:30.580
And if you could plot it, you
could say, here's a maximum,

00:49:30.580 --> 00:49:32.360
here's a minimum.

00:49:32.360 --> 00:49:35.427
If you want to figure out
where they are, you know.

00:49:35.427 --> 00:49:38.050
You take a derivative,
set it equal to 0,

00:49:38.050 --> 00:49:41.300
you find the maxima and minima.

00:49:41.300 --> 00:49:44.030
So the typical
calculus problem is

00:49:44.030 --> 00:49:45.635
one in which you
have a function,

00:49:45.635 --> 00:49:47.930
and you want the
maxima and minima.

00:49:47.930 --> 00:49:51.920
The variational
problem is a problem

00:49:51.920 --> 00:49:56.190
in which you want to maximize
or minimize something.

00:49:56.190 --> 00:50:00.890
But what you don't know is not
where the maximum or minimum

00:50:00.890 --> 00:50:04.440
occurs, but which
kind of function

00:50:04.440 --> 00:50:07.090
will give you this
maximum or minimum.

00:50:07.090 --> 00:50:09.890
So your unknown is
not a point where

00:50:09.890 --> 00:50:13.790
there's a maximum or a
minimum but a function where

00:50:13.790 --> 00:50:16.310
there is a maximum
and a minimum.

00:50:16.310 --> 00:50:20.660
So it's slightly
more complicated.

00:50:20.660 --> 00:50:22.940
So this is the
calculus of variations.

00:50:22.940 --> 00:50:28.290
And people wonder
when did it start.

00:50:28.290 --> 00:50:31.530
It actually seems to have
first been discussed by Newton.

00:50:31.530 --> 00:50:36.080
And it's quite an
interesting story.

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:39.060
Newton was trying to
understand apparently

00:50:39.060 --> 00:50:40.470
the following problem.

00:50:40.470 --> 00:50:49.610
If you would have a cross
sectional area like this,

00:50:49.610 --> 00:50:53.700
he asked the question,
how should you

00:50:53.700 --> 00:50:59.640
make a solid out of this
by tapering it and ending

00:50:59.640 --> 00:51:02.810
with this, tapering
it, in such a way

00:51:02.810 --> 00:51:06.070
that as it moves
in a viscous fluid,

00:51:06.070 --> 00:51:10.980
the resistance is the minimum
possible-- very complicated

00:51:10.980 --> 00:51:12.950
problem.

00:51:12.950 --> 00:51:16.180
And as you can imagine, this
is a complicated problem

00:51:16.180 --> 00:51:19.590
because you're trying to find
a shape-- not just a maximum

00:51:19.590 --> 00:51:22.060
or a minimum of a
function but what

00:51:22.060 --> 00:51:25.930
shape maximizes
or minimizes this.

00:51:25.930 --> 00:51:28.600
So apparently, he
solved the problem

00:51:28.600 --> 00:51:33.950
and wrote it in Principia but
didn't explain his solution.

00:51:33.950 --> 00:51:36.650
And people for years were
trying to figure it out.

00:51:36.650 --> 00:51:41.130
And nobody could figure
out how he did it.

00:51:41.130 --> 00:51:47.710
Then, the story goes that this
mathematician Johann Bernoulli

00:51:47.710 --> 00:51:53.870
in 1696 came up with a
challenge to all mathematicians.

00:51:53.870 --> 00:51:56.380
At that time, people
would announce a problem

00:51:56.380 --> 00:51:59.110
and challenge to
see who's smart,

00:51:59.110 --> 00:52:01.580
who can solve this problem.

00:52:01.580 --> 00:52:13.380
So Johann Bernoulli
in around 1696

00:52:13.380 --> 00:52:18.410
poses a problem of, you're
given two points in the plane,

00:52:18.410 --> 00:52:23.440
in the vertical plane like
this blackboard, point this, A,

00:52:23.440 --> 00:52:28.560
and point B in here.

00:52:28.560 --> 00:52:32.260
You must design the
curve of shortest time

00:52:32.260 --> 00:52:35.430
for fall, so some curve here.

00:52:35.430 --> 00:52:37.465
If you put an object
and let it fall,

00:52:37.465 --> 00:52:42.270
it will get the fastest
to that point, so maybe

00:52:42.270 --> 00:52:44.950
something that looks like this.

00:52:44.950 --> 00:52:49.860
It's a complicated curve, or
at least not all that simple.

00:52:49.860 --> 00:52:56.330
And he asked all the
people to solve it,

00:52:56.330 --> 00:53:00.740
gave them one year to solve it.

00:53:00.740 --> 00:53:03.920
So who was around at that time?

00:53:03.920 --> 00:53:08.060
Well, one person that got
the letter was Leibniz.

00:53:08.060 --> 00:53:12.800
He got it on the 9th of
June of that year, 1696.

00:53:12.800 --> 00:53:17.340
And he answered it,
sent an email back,

00:53:17.340 --> 00:53:20.000
by the 16th of
June with a letter

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:21.285
with a complete solution.

00:53:24.470 --> 00:53:29.640
It's a funny thing that actually
apparently Newton was very busy

00:53:29.640 --> 00:53:32.540
and didn't receive this letter.

00:53:32.540 --> 00:53:35.510
Or something happened,
and he got it one day,

00:53:35.510 --> 00:53:39.750
and he actually solved
the problem in one night.

00:53:39.750 --> 00:53:43.170
It took him one full
night to solve it.

00:53:43.170 --> 00:53:45.090
Now, you say, well,
how brilliant.

00:53:45.090 --> 00:53:49.670
And true, but given that
he had solved this problem,

00:53:49.670 --> 00:53:54.590
he was criticized as being
really slow and-- how come

00:53:54.590 --> 00:53:56.680
you took 12 hours to
solve this problem?

00:54:00.250 --> 00:54:02.210
So it's quite amazing.

00:54:02.210 --> 00:54:03.980
There's a lot of Bernoullis.

00:54:03.980 --> 00:54:08.970
And apparently, this
question by Jacob Bernoulli,

00:54:08.970 --> 00:54:11.990
the main purpose
of this question

00:54:11.990 --> 00:54:16.820
was to demonstrate to everybody
that his older brother,

00:54:16.820 --> 00:54:20.640
Jacob Bernoulli, who had
invented the Bernoulli numbers,

00:54:20.640 --> 00:54:22.790
was actually an
incompetent person that

00:54:22.790 --> 00:54:25.990
could not solve this problem.

00:54:25.990 --> 00:54:29.110
So that was apparently
what he wanted to do.

00:54:29.110 --> 00:54:31.650
It's a rather famous family.

00:54:31.650 --> 00:54:34.000
But they obviously
didn't get along.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:37.330
But apparently, Jacob did
manage to solve the problem.

00:54:37.330 --> 00:54:41.515
So Jacob Bernoulli, Leibniz, and
Newton all solved the problem.

00:54:44.130 --> 00:54:47.670
Johann Bernoulli, the one that
started this problem-- and I

00:54:47.670 --> 00:54:50.220
think it's maybe
with a double N,

00:54:50.220 --> 00:54:54.510
I'm sorry-- his son
is Daniel Bernoulli.

00:54:54.510 --> 00:54:56.470
And engineers know
him, because that's

00:54:56.470 --> 00:55:01.160
the Bernoulli of the Bernoulli
fluid dynamics stuff.

00:55:01.160 --> 00:55:05.775
So the problem is
not all that easy.

00:55:05.775 --> 00:55:09.490
And calculus of variations
determines this shape.

00:55:09.490 --> 00:55:14.580
So the calculus of variation
applied to quantum mechanics

00:55:14.580 --> 00:55:21.000
asks, here, this function is
determined by the principle

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:24.250
that it minimizes time.

00:55:24.250 --> 00:55:26.730
So you have the
Schrodinger Equation.

00:55:26.730 --> 00:55:31.130
And you could ask, you have
all these Eigenfunctions.

00:55:31.130 --> 00:55:33.870
What do they minimize?

00:55:33.870 --> 00:55:36.610
Is there something
they're minimize?

00:55:36.610 --> 00:55:38.230
And the answer is yes.

00:55:38.230 --> 00:55:40.510
And this is what
you'll understand

00:55:40.510 --> 00:55:43.330
in the next few minutes.

00:55:43.330 --> 00:55:46.060
So what is the problem
we want to solve?

00:55:46.060 --> 00:55:52.280
We want to solve the
problem h psi equal e psi.

00:55:52.280 --> 00:55:54.670
So some Hamiltonian.

00:55:54.670 --> 00:56:00.390
Now my notation
will be such that it

00:56:00.390 --> 00:56:02.740
applies to three
dimensions as well.

00:56:02.740 --> 00:56:04.990
So I'll put just
arrows on top of it,

00:56:04.990 --> 00:56:07.850
and you would have to write
the proper Hamiltonian.

00:56:07.850 --> 00:56:11.690
It will not be necessary for
you to know the Hamiltonian.

00:56:11.690 --> 00:56:15.890
So I'll put psi
of x here, meaning

00:56:15.890 --> 00:56:21.360
that this is equally valid
for more than one dimension.

00:56:21.360 --> 00:56:28.200
Now we want to find
solutions of this equation.

00:56:28.200 --> 00:56:30.870
And you can say, what do
they maximize or minimize?

00:56:30.870 --> 00:56:33.600
Well we won't get to
it until 15 minutes.

00:56:33.600 --> 00:56:37.110
First let's try
something simpler.

00:56:37.110 --> 00:56:39.740
How about, can we
learn something

00:56:39.740 --> 00:56:43.950
about the ground state
energy of the system?

00:56:43.950 --> 00:56:48.360
So let's try to think about
the ground state energy.

00:56:50.950 --> 00:56:53.240
State energy.

00:57:00.670 --> 00:57:05.440
Now consider ground
state energy and we'll

00:57:05.440 --> 00:57:14.390
consider an
arbitrary-- arbitrary

00:57:14.390 --> 00:57:17.960
is the most
important word here--

00:57:17.960 --> 00:57:20.103
psi of x that is normalized.

00:57:23.070 --> 00:57:23.722
Is normalized.

00:57:26.600 --> 00:57:34.020
So integral the x of psi
squared is equal to 1.

00:57:39.480 --> 00:57:42.800
And here comes the claim.

00:57:42.800 --> 00:57:49.030
The first claim
that we can make.

00:57:49.030 --> 00:57:51.470
You see, this wave
function doesn't

00:57:51.470 --> 00:57:53.450
solve the Schrodinger equation.

00:57:53.450 --> 00:57:56.390
That's what we
mean by arbitrary.

00:57:56.390 --> 00:58:02.950
It's just any function of
space that is normalizable.

00:58:02.950 --> 00:58:04.980
Doesn't solve the
Schrodinger equation.

00:58:04.980 --> 00:58:07.110
Never the less,
you are commanded

