01:16:58.750 --> 01:17:07.100
over 2m d-2nd dx2nd
minus alpha delta of x.

01:17:07.100 --> 01:17:09.910
And another wave function,
e to the minus one

01:17:09.910 --> 01:17:13.980
half beta squared x-2nd.

01:17:13.980 --> 01:17:14.650
OK.

01:17:14.650 --> 01:17:16.390
So you have to evaluate that.

01:17:16.390 --> 01:17:20.096
And that's the part
that is not so much fun.

01:17:20.096 --> 01:17:23.760
For any integral
that you have in 805,

01:17:23.760 --> 01:17:29.340
we believe that you can use
Mathematica or Maple or MATLAB

01:17:29.340 --> 01:17:31.220
or whatever and do it.

01:17:31.220 --> 01:17:34.550
The only reason not to
use any of these things

01:17:34.550 --> 01:17:37.240
is if you think you could
not do the integral.

01:17:37.240 --> 01:17:39.490
But once you realize,
oh, this is an integral,

01:17:39.490 --> 01:17:42.720
I know how to do,
don't waste time.

01:17:42.720 --> 01:17:44.340
Use any of those programs.

01:17:44.340 --> 01:17:48.400
Now, this part of the
integral is kind of easy

01:17:48.400 --> 01:17:51.610
because the delta function
just picks the value of 0.

01:17:51.610 --> 01:17:56.020
So this part of the
integral gives you

01:17:56.020 --> 01:18:00.780
minus beta alpha over
square root of pi.

01:18:00.780 --> 01:18:03.530
The other part of the
integral, however,

01:18:03.530 --> 01:18:06.120
is a little more complicated.

01:18:06.120 --> 01:18:10.240
Believe it or not, it
makes a big difference

01:18:10.240 --> 01:18:12.110
whether you take
the two derivatives

01:18:12.110 --> 01:18:14.710
of this function or
you integrate by parts.

01:18:14.710 --> 01:18:18.500
If you integrate by parts,
you save a lot of work.

01:18:18.500 --> 01:18:20.910
So let me integrate by parts.

01:18:20.910 --> 01:18:26.120
This becomes, plus beta
over square root of h,

01:18:26.120 --> 01:18:32.320
h-2nd over 2m,
integral dx of ddx of e

01:18:32.320 --> 01:18:38.590
to the minus one half beta
squared x-2nd squared.

01:18:38.590 --> 01:18:41.850
So you integrate by
parts one of the ddx

01:18:41.850 --> 01:18:46.020
and then you have the other
ddx, so it's the thing squared.

01:18:46.020 --> 01:18:51.250
And that's an easier
integral to do.

01:18:51.250 --> 01:18:53.850
We don't want to
bother with this,

01:18:53.850 --> 01:18:58.280
but this whole
thing then becomes

01:18:58.280 --> 01:19:04.750
minus beta over square root of
pi, alpha plus beta squared h

01:19:04.750 --> 01:19:06.450
squared over 4m.

01:19:06.450 --> 01:19:11.740
That's the whole
answer And that's

01:19:11.740 --> 01:19:16.330
the valuation of
this whole thing.

01:19:16.330 --> 01:19:18.490
So look what you get.

01:19:18.490 --> 01:19:21.770
You got a function
of beta indeed.

01:19:21.770 --> 01:19:24.800
So how does that
function of beta look?

01:19:24.800 --> 01:19:29.850
It's 0 for beta equals 0 is 0
for some other possible beta,

01:19:29.850 --> 01:19:31.860
it's going to look like this.

01:19:31.860 --> 01:19:34.320
So there's a point at
which this function is

01:19:34.320 --> 01:19:37.800
going to have a minimum, and
we should choose that point

01:19:37.800 --> 01:19:41.545
to get the best upper
bound on the function.

01:19:45.270 --> 01:19:53.040
Our claim is that following
from the variational theorem

01:19:53.040 --> 01:19:55.690
that we've proven
is that the e ground

01:19:55.690 --> 01:20:03.220
state is less than or equal
than the minimum value over beta

01:20:03.220 --> 01:20:09.050
of this beta squared
h squared over 4m

01:20:09.050 --> 01:20:12.875
minus beta square
root of pie alpha.

01:20:12.875 --> 01:20:17.150
So you minimize over beta,
and yet still the ground state

01:20:17.150 --> 01:20:21.440
energy must be a little
smaller than that.

01:20:21.440 --> 01:20:22.860
Well what do you get?

01:20:25.790 --> 01:20:29.910
You do this, this minimization
gives beta equal 2m

01:20:29.910 --> 01:20:34.660
alpha over h squared
square root of pi.

01:20:34.660 --> 01:20:37.190
It's a little messy
but not terrible.

01:20:37.190 --> 01:20:41.230
And you substitute, and you
get that e ground state is

01:20:41.230 --> 01:20:49.140
less than or equal than m alpha
squared over pi h squared.

01:20:49.140 --> 01:20:56.400
And to better write it as 2
over pi times minus m alpha

01:20:56.400 --> 01:21:02.300
squared over 2h-2nd which is
the true ground state energy.

01:21:02.300 --> 01:21:06.660
So let's just make sure we
understand what has happened.

01:21:06.660 --> 01:21:08.640
Here is the energy.

01:21:08.640 --> 01:21:10.880
Here is zero.

01:21:10.880 --> 01:21:15.360
Energy as just a vertical
plot here is zero.

01:21:15.360 --> 01:21:20.350
The true ground state
energy of this problem

01:21:20.350 --> 01:21:25.280
is this one, let's call
it egs, is negative.

01:21:25.280 --> 01:21:27.970
And we go 2 over pi times that.

01:21:27.970 --> 01:21:33.200
2 over pi is about 0.64.

01:21:33.200 --> 01:21:40.560
So the bound says
that here is 0.64 egs.

01:21:40.560 --> 01:21:44.650
So that's what the
bound told you.

01:21:44.650 --> 01:21:49.180
The bound state energy must
be lower than this quantity.

01:21:49.180 --> 01:21:50.490
We got close.

01:21:50.490 --> 01:21:53.590
Not impressively
close, but the work

01:21:53.590 --> 01:21:55.850
functional was not
all that bad either.

01:21:58.800 --> 01:21:59.966
Question?

01:21:59.966 --> 01:22:01.830
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
always going

01:22:01.830 --> 01:22:04.160
to be a constant times
incorrect energy value

01:22:04.160 --> 01:22:06.750
or is it just the
closest approximation?

01:22:06.750 --> 01:22:08.360
PROFESSOR: Is it
going to be what?

01:22:08.360 --> 01:22:10.176
AUDIENCE: Is it
always going to be

01:22:10.176 --> 01:22:12.936
a constant times the correct
energy value or is it just--

01:22:12.936 --> 01:22:14.890
PROFESSOR: Well it
typically is like that

01:22:14.890 --> 01:22:19.000
because of dimensional units.

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:21.900
You're looking for a
constant because you're not

01:22:21.900 --> 01:22:23.150
looking for the function.

01:22:23.150 --> 01:22:28.590
So you will get a number times
a correct value, yes, indeed.

01:22:28.590 --> 01:22:33.646
That's an illustration of the
problem of wave functions.

01:22:33.646 --> 01:22:36.310
You know the variational
principle tells you

01:22:36.310 --> 01:22:38.310
things about the
ground state but allows

01:22:38.310 --> 01:22:41.620
you to find the first
excited state as well

01:22:41.620 --> 01:22:45.570
if the potential is symmetric,
will allow you to prove

01:22:45.570 --> 01:22:49.060
that any attractive
potential has a bound state.

01:22:49.060 --> 01:22:51.750
And you will prove
in the homework

01:22:51.750 --> 01:22:56.040
that stationary points of these
things are the eigenfunctions.

